        {
          "type": "explanation",
          "name": "breaking effect",
          "definition": "Controls particle velocities when a damage effect shatters a materal.\n\nAll particles created within 'forward radius' will be kicked along the\ndamage direction with a speed equivalent to 'forward velocity' at the\nepicenter of the damage and 0 at the outer radius.  'Forward exponent'\nis used to modify the velocity scale.  A low exponent (like 0.5) means that\nparticles between the epicenter and the radius will be kicked out with a speed\ncloser to 'forward velocity' than if a higher exponent (like 2.0) was used\n\nThe outward fields work in a similar way, except instead of kicking along the\ndamage direction, they get kick away from the damage epicenter."
        },
        {
          "type": "real",
          "name": "forward velocity:world units per second"
        },
        {
          "type": "real",
          "name": "forward radius:world units"
        },
        {
          "type": "real",
          "name": "forward exponent"
        },
        {
          "type": "useless_pad",
          "name": null,
          "definition": 12
        },
        {
          "type": "real",
          "name": "outward velocity:world units per second"
        },
        {
          "type": "real",
          "name": "outward radius:world units"
        },
        {
          "type": "real",
          "name": "outward exponent"
        },
        {
          "type": "useless_pad",
          "name": null,
          "definition": 12
        },
